text:
Relationships are actually simple once you understand that no one wants to take responsibility for where you are in life.

Fix your health, your finances, your insecurities; clarify your purpose, become a reliable person for your family, clarify the kind of person you need to become to deserve better friends;

and suddenly, you will start making a lot of wonderful serendipitous encounters with people who care, and these relationships will last.

Treat older people like you will want to be treated;

treat younger people like you wanted to be treated;

treat people the same age like you are going to make the world a better place together.

“A ‘brand’ originally meant a burn mark on livestock. It’s ironic that people feel awe toward that mark, long for its authority, and pay large sums to obtain it, essentially buying a modern version of a livestock brand.”

Great post as always.

@EDWD14007070

Life gets better once you finally become honest with yourself and hit yourself with the painful truths:

You are poor because you didn’t bother taking financial risks ten years ago;

you are low-energy because you didn’t bother changing your lifestyle ten years ago;

you are lonely because you didn’t bother investing in relationships with thoughtful people ten years ago;

you are unattractive because you didn't bother treating yourself with attention and care ten years ago;

you are insecure because you didn’t bother following through the efforts you started ten years ago;

you are confused because you didn’t bother investing in your own mind ten years ago;

you are angry because you didn’t bother listening to the feedback from reality ten years ago;

you are unlucky because you didn’t bother thinking deeply before making your big decisions ten years ago of where to live, what to work on, and who to spend your time with.

It’s not that life is too short and we never have enough time to do all the things we want to do;

it’s more like we are afraid of making clear choices, we don’t want to close some certain doors to open some uncertain others, we refuse to take a leap of faith and commit more deeply:

a lot of your achievements simply reflect your courage to say “no” in order to keep your energy for the things that truly matter in the long run.

Great outcomes usually require trade-offs and sacrifices, but you don't have to neglect your physical and mental health;

too many people are somehow proud of not having enough time to sleep, exercise, enjoy their meals, watch their kids grow, share meaningful conversations with their family and friends;

many unhappy people love to say the contrary, but it's entirely possible to reach your goals and enjoy the journey too, you just need to understand your strengths better than anyone else;

don't wait until you are old to realize that you spent your whole life walking on a path that someone else wanted you to walk.

Lifelong friendships are actually simple:

be the better friend, be thoughtful, be supportive, reach out to others, do it because you genuinely care;

and as the years pass, some bonds will fade away, usually the ones with people who never really cared much, that’s fine, respect yourself and let go;

one day, you will look back, and find yourself surrounded by the very family and friends that you deserve, people who will make you feel grateful that you got to share together many meaningful chapters, people who will be a reflection of who you were as a person.

It’s not selfish to take care of yourself and live a fun, wealthy, happy life;

it’s actually selfish to not have your life together and be a constant burden on everyone around you,

either because you are constantly low-energy, emotionally unstable, or financially irresponsible.

When you are serious about a goal, things like lack of money, lack of time, lack of connections, lack of talent, are all excuses;

you would figure out how to get the money even if it temporarily involves work you couldn't care less about;

you would figure out how to make more time even if it involves a few sacrifices in terms of hobbies and fun;

you would figure out how to be in the right place where better serendipitous encounters can happen even if it involves leaving a few people behind;

you would figure out how become the more talented version of yourself even if it involves a lot of training that might not be enjoyable in the first place.

When you look back, it’s really obvious that life kept sending you exactly who you needed to meet, to learn from, to teach you an important lesson, to give you a life-changing opportunity; 

it just happens that because of your ego, pride, judgmental stance, you ended up missing out, but that wasn’t because life was unfair, but because you were wrongly convinced that you knew better.

The best people rarely tell you what you did wrong; they have better to do than argue with people who can’t admit it when they are wrong; if you are worthy of them, they will stick around; otherwise, they will quietly vanish.

At least once in their lives, most people usually have the "opportunity" to hit rock bottom and rebuild themselves better, especially when they still have nearly nothing to lose;

the real difficulty begins when you have enough to lose, not enough to win, and start playing "safe," until you notice, way too late, that you ended up actually never truly living at all;

that's why you see so many people who seem to be doing relatively well from the point of view of conventional success, and yet, who also seem quite disconnected emotionally and not having fun at all in their daily lives.

When it comes to investing, swimming against the tide and being right once with enough conviction will earn you a lifetime of wealth;

when it comes to building a happy life, swimming against the tide is often a recipe to become a jaded, frustrated, angry version of yourself.

If you are living in a place where you need to constantly fight to be respected and accepted, you're gonna waste all your energy just to build an average life.

Your "home" will be a place where your common sense and values will be aligned with everyone else's;

you will be able to focus on becoming who you want to be, you will be able to build a circle of loyal family and friends, you will be able to leverage your talents and create what you are uniquely suited for.

Life doesn't care about your efforts, it only cares about efforts made in the right direction, and it all begins with being in the right environment.

There are many smart and creative kids who wanted to pursue an artistic career, who were also too pragmatic and responsible to take the jump because their family struggled financially;

and by the time they reached a bit of financial security, they no longer enjoyed books, music, art like they used to, and that's a very tragic sight, because you can never be the most joyful, happy, alive version of yourself as long as you forgot about who you were meant to be;

that's how you end up with so many adults who may have covered their materialistic needs, but who also seem emotionally absent, disconnected from who they forgot they wanted to be: present, playful, creative; they have money without wealth, games without fun, goals without purpose.

When you have freedom but no clear goal, you waste your time;

when you have a clear goal but no freedom, you get anxious about your wasted potential;

when you have a clear goal and the freedom to pursue it, you grow into the most high-energy and confident version of yourself.
